litical functions of scientific research and economic advisors for Britain at a moment in which Caribbean governments operated with increasing autonomy and the US was intent on expanding its influence in the region. Britain's preferred path to industrial development was threatened by an alternative promoted through the Caribbean Commission. The provision of knowledge and expertise became key routes by which Britain and America competed to shape the future of the region, and their place in it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aColonies and colonization. Emigration and immigration. International migration. 0aCommerce. 0aScience (General). 4aStudies in Imperialism 2019. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aCaribbean.  adevelopment.  aempire.  aexperts.  aindustrialisation.  alate colonial.  ascience.  asugar.1 aClarke, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packagez978311128277040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526131409zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526131409zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526131409/original  a978-3-11-128277-0 Manchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packageb2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA